The paper deals with scheduling in interference networks, which is a topic that falls under the sub-categories of information theory (cs.IT), networking and internet architecture (cs.NI), systems and control (cs.SY), multimedia (cs.MM), and distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC). The paper proposes a distributed algorithm that leverages the physical layer capabilities of the network to achieve higher rates, which is a problem that is relevant to all of these sub-categories. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.IT, cs.NI, and cs.SY, followed by cs.MM and cs.DC.
